From: gcc-for-Windows98 build pipeline
Subject: [PATCH] skip NT security stubs on Win98 (_WIN98_PORT)

busybox-w32 calls a handful of advapi32 NT-security APIs that exist as
exports on Win98 SE's ADVAPI32.DLL but are stubs that always return
failure on the Win9x kernel. The static PE imports bind cleanly at load
time but a Win98-aware verifier rightly rejects them — we shouldn't ship
binaries that depend on functions the platform can't honor.

Three call-site clusters in win32/mingw.c, each its own self-contained
function:

  * file_owner()       — uses OpenProcessToken / GetTokenInformation /
                         DuplicateToken / GetSecurityInfo / EqualSid /
                         AccessCheck for security-aware UID lookup on
                         file ownership (ENABLE_FEATURE_EXTRA_FILE_DATA).
  * gethomedir()       — uses OpenProcessToken + GetUserProfileDirectoryA
                         (the latter via INIT_PROC_ADDR) for $HOME lookup.
  * elevation_state()  — uses OpenProcessToken / GetTokenInformation
                         (TokenElevation) for the admin-detection probe
                         consumed by getuid() and the suw32 applet.

The original code already handles call failure gracefully (returns
DEFAULT_UID / empty buffer / 0), so the Win98 path simply short-circuits
to those defaults at the top of each function. Defining -D_WIN98_PORT
during compilation switches in those short-circuits; without it the
upstream code is preserved verbatim, so this patch is a no-op for the
non-Win98 mingw-w64 path.

This keeps the busybox applet surface intact (id / whoami / ls -l /
stat / su all keep working with their "anonymous, non-admin, default
home" fallbacks) while preventing the linker from pulling stub-only
NT-security imports into the PE.

--- a/win32/mingw.c
+++ b/win32/mingw.c
@@ -564,6 +564,14 @@
 #if ENABLE_FEATURE_EXTRA_FILE_DATA
 static uid_t file_owner(HANDLE fh, struct mingw_stat *buf)
 {
+#ifdef _WIN98_PORT
+	/* Win9x advapi32 exports NT security APIs as stubs that bind but
+	 * always fail at runtime (OpenProcessToken / GetTokenInformation /
+	 * GetSecurityInfo / EqualSid / AccessCheck / DuplicateToken).
+	 * Single-user system: every file "owned" by the only user. */
+	(void)fh; (void)buf;
+	return DEFAULT_UID;
+#else
 	PSID pSidOwner;
 	PACL pDACL;
 	PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR pSD;
@@ -646,6 +654,7 @@
 	}
 	LocalFree(pSD);
 	return uid;
+#endif /* _WIN98_PORT */
 }
 #endif

@@ -1208,6 +1217,13 @@

 static char *gethomedir(void)
 {
+#ifdef _WIN98_PORT
+	/* Win9x has no NT user-profile directory. Return an empty static
+	 * buffer (same observable behavior as the NT path failing). */
+	static char *empty_buf = NULL;
+	if (!empty_buf) empty_buf = xzalloc(PATH_MAX);
+	return empty_buf;
+#else
 	static char *buf = NULL;
 	DECLARE_PROC_ADDR(BOOL, GetUserProfileDirectoryA, HANDLE, LPSTR, LPDWORD);

@@ -1225,6 +1241,7 @@
 		}
 	}
 	return buf;
+#endif /* _WIN98_PORT */
 }

 #define NAME_LEN 100
@@ -1263,6 +1280,11 @@
 int
 elevation_state(void)
 {
+#ifdef _WIN98_PORT
+	/* Win9x has no NT process tokens or group memberships: every process
+	 * is the (sole) user. Not elevated, not admin. */
+	return 0;
+#else
 	int elevated = FALSE;
 	int enabled = TRUE;
 	HANDLE h;
@@ -1292,6 +1314,7 @@
 #endif

 	return elevated | (enabled << 1);
+#endif /* _WIN98_PORT */
 }

 int getuid(void)
